+## Amendment 1: PGSD kernel offer runs last (kernel-last ordering)
+
+Proposed 2026-06-18 (pending operator ratification).
+
+### Context
+
+After this ADR was accepted, `install.sh` gained an interactive offer to build
+and install the PGSD kernel when the host is running GENERIC. The first
+implementation placed that offer early in Phase 1, before the kernel-module
+deploy, and stopped after the kernel install to require a reboot and a re-run
+for the rest of the install.
+
+A bench on 2026-06-18 showed that ordering is unsafe. The PGSD kernel drops the
+in-tree framebuffer console drivers, so a host that boots PGSD with no
+`drawfs.ko` present comes up dark. `pgsd-kernel-build.sh`'s AD-8 closure
+verification encodes exactly that invariant and fails with `/boot/modules/
+drawfs.ko missing`, refusing to bless the kernel until `drawfs.ko` is deployed.
+`install.sh` deploys `drawfs.ko` in Phase 2, after the early kernel block, so
+the invariant could never hold under the original ordering: the closure check
+failed on the bench and the install aborted with the kernel already swapped into
+`/boot/kernel` but no `drawfs.ko` staged.
+
+### Decision
+
+The PGSD kernel offer runs as the final install activity, at the end of Phase 2,
+after the full deploy (the `drawfs.ko` and `inputfs.ko` builds, `drawfs_load`,
+the binary installs, and the service setup). By that point `drawfs.ko` is in
+`/boot/modules/` and `drawfs_load="YES"` is set, so the AD-8 closure check
+passes. After a successful kernel install the operator reboots straight into a
+ready system; there is no second install pass.
+
+The earlier "kernel first, reboot, then re-run the rest" model is withdrawn.
+There is no technical need to build the rest of the install on the PGSD kernel:
+the modules build against `/usr/src`, not the running kernel, so modules built
+under GENERIC load under PGSD of the same FreeBSD version. And the
+reboot-then-rerun model cannot satisfy the closure invariant, because it would
+have to deploy `drawfs.ko` only after the reboot that already needs it.
+
+### Consequences
+
+1. The offer is interactive only. A `--yes` or non-tty run notes that GENERIC is
+   in use and that the kernel build is skipped, then completes normally; the
+   installer never compiles a kernel unattended.
+2. Because this phase already runs as root via the `$PRIV` re-exec, the kernel
+   build and install delegate to `pgsd-kernel-build.sh` directly, without a
+   further `priv` hop. `AWASE_KERNCONF` (default `PGSD`) is passed through the
+   re-exec so `PGSD-DEBUG` selection survives into Phase 2.
+3. `pgsd-kernel-build.sh` remains the single source of truth for source-tree
+   validation, AD-8 closure, recovery checks, and build flags. `install.sh` only
+   sequences the `check`, `build`, and `install` phases and preserves their
+   operator checkpoints, so a check warning or a failed world or kernel build
+   stops for inspection rather than scrolling past inside the install.
+4. A build or install failure at this stage is not fatal to the Awase install,
+   which is already complete and runs on GENERIC; the installer reports the
+   failure, leaves GENERIC bootable, and exits non-zero.
+
+### Closure
+
+Bench on a fresh install (operator, pgsd-bare-metal):
+
+1. GENERIC host, full `sh install.sh`, accept the offer: the AD-8 closure check
+   passes (drawfs.ko present) and the run stops with the reboot-into-a-ready-
+   system message.
+2. Re-run with `--yes`: the kernel build is skipped with the GENERIC note and
+   the install completes.
+3. After rebooting into PGSD, re-run `sh install.sh`: no kernel offer appears
+   (`uname -i` reports PGSD).
+
+Flip this amendment to Accepted once item 1 passes; items 2 and 3 confirm the
+non-interactive and already-PGSD paths.
